SIMPLE: pass
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pass
<hw>Pass</hw> <pr>(p⟦adot⟧s, p⟦acr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Passed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Passing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>passer</ets>, LL. <ets>passare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>passus</ets>
step, or from <ets>pandere</ets>, <ets>passum</ets>, to spread out, lay
open. See <er>Pace</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go; to move; to
proceed; to be moved or transferred from one point to another; to make a
transit; -- usually with a following adverb or adverbal phrase defining
the kind or manner of motion; <as>as, to <ex>pass</ex> on, by, out, in,
etc.; to <ex>pass</ex> swiftly, directly, smoothly, etc.; to
<ex>pass</ex> to the rear, under the yoke, over the bridge, across the
field, beyond the border, etc.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧But now <xex>pass</xex>
over [i. e., <xex>pass</xex> on].⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On high behests his angels to and fro⟦br⟧
<qex>Passed</qex> frequent.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sweet sounds rose slowly through their mouths,⟦br⟧
And from their bodies <qex>passed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move or be transferred from one state or
condition to another; to change possession, condition, or circumstances;
to undergo transition; <as>as, the business has <ex>passed</ex> into
other hands</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Others, dissatisfied with what they have, . . . <qex>pass</qex>
from just to unjust.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move beyond the range of the senses or of
knowledge; to pass away; hence, to disappear; to vanish; to depart;
specifically, to depart from life; to die.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Disturb him not, let him <qex>pass</qex> paceably.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beauty is a charm, but soon the charm will <qex>pass</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>passing</qex> of the sweetest soul⟦br⟧
That ever looked with human eyes.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move or to come into being or under notice; to
come and go in consciousness; hence, to take place; to occur; to happen;
to come; to occur progressively or in succession; to be present
transitorily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So death <qex>passed</qex> upon all men.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. v.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our own consciousness of what <qex>passes</qex> within our own
mind.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To go by or glide by, as time; to elapse; to be
spent; <as>as, their vacation <ex>passed</ex> pleasantly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now the time is far <qex>passed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mark vi.
35</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To go from one person to another; hence, to be given
and taken freely; <as>as, clipped coin will not <ex>pass</ex></as>; to
obtain general acceptance; to be held or regarded; to circulate; to be
current; -- followed by <xex>for</xex> before a word denoting value or
estimation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Let him <xex>pass</xex> for a man.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>False eloquence <qex>passeth</qex> only where true is not
understood.</q> <rj><qau>Felton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This will not <qex>pass</qex> for a fault in him.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To advance through all the steps or stages necessary
to validity or effectiveness; to be carried through a body that has
power to sanction or reject; to receive legislative sanction; to be
enacted; <as>as, the resolution <ex>passed</ex>; the bill
<ex>passed</ex> both houses of Congress.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To go through any inspection or test successfully;
to be approved or accepted; <as>as, he attempted the examination, but
did not expect to <ex>pass</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To be suffered to go on; to be tolerated; hence, to
continue; to live along.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The play may
<xex>pass</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To go unheeded or neglected; to proceed without
hindrance or opposition; <as>as, we let this act
<ex>pass</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To go beyond bounds; to surpass; to be in
excess.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧This <xex>passes</xex>, Master
Ford.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To take heed; to care.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for these silken-coated slaves, I <qex>pass</qex> not.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To go through the intestines.</def>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To be conveyed or transferred by
will, deed, or other instrument of conveyance; <as>as, an estate
<ex>passes</ex> by a certain clause in a deed</as>.</def> <rj><au>Mozley
& W.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Fencing)</fld> <def>To make a lunge or pass; to
thrust.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>To decline to play in
one's turn; in euchre, to decline to make the trump.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She would not play, yet must not <qex>pass</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To bring to pass</b></col>, <col><b>To come to
pass</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Bring</er>, and
<er>Come</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass away</b></col>, <cd>to disappear;
to die; to vanish.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The heavens shall <xex>pass
away</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>2 Pet. iii. 10.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧I thought to
<xex>pass away</xex> before, but yet alive I am.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Tennyson.</au> -- <col><b>To pass by</b></col>, <cd>to go near and
beyond a certain person or place; as, he <xex>passed by</xex> as we
stood there.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass into</b></col>, <cd>to change by a
gradual transmission; to blend or unite with.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass
on</b></col>, <cd>to proceed.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To pass on</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To pass upon</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
happen to; to come upon; to affect</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧So death <xex>passed
upon</xex> all men.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Rom. v. 12.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Provided no
indirect act <xex>pass upon</xex> our prayers to define them.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Jer. Taylor.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To determine concerning; to give
judgment or sentence upon.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧We may not <xex>pass upon</xex>
his life.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To pass off</b></col>, <cd>to
go away; to cease; to disappear; <as>as, an agitation <ex>passes
off</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass over</b></col>, <cd>to go from
one side or end to the other; to cross, as a river, road, or
bridge.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pass</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pass
<hw>Pass</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> In simple,
transitive senses; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To go by, beyond, over,
through, or the like; to proceed from one side to the other of; <as>as,
to <ex>pass</ex> a house, a stream, a boundary, etc.</as></def>
<sd>(b)</sd> Hence: <def>To go from one limit to the other of; to spend;
to live through; to have experience of; to undergo; to suffer.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>pass</xex> commodiously this life.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She loved me for the dangers I had <qex>passed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To go by without noticing; to omit attention to; to
take no note of; to disregard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Please you that I may <qex>pass</qex> This doing.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>pass</qex> their warlike pomp, their proud array.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To transcend; to surpass; to excel; to
exceed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And strive to <qex>pass</qex> . . . ⟦br⟧
Their native music by her skillful art.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose tender power⟦br⟧
<qex>Passes</qex> the strength of storms in their most desolate
hour.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>To go successfully through, as an examination,
trail, test, etc.; to obtain the formal sanction of, as a legislative
body; <as>as, he <ex>passed</ex> his examination; the bill
<ex>passed</ex> the senate</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> In causative senses: as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To cause to
move or go; to send; to transfer from one person, place, or condition to
another; to transmit; to deliver; to hand; to make over; <as>as, the
waiter <ex>passed</ex> bisquit and cheese; the torch was <ex>passed</ex>
from hand to hand</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had only time to <qex>pass</qex> my eye over the medals.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Waller <qex>passed</qex> over five thousand horse and foot by
Newbridge.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To cause to pass the lips; to utter; to pronounce;
hence, to promise; to pledge; <as>as, to <ex>pass</ex>
sentence</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Father, thy word is <qex>passed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To cause to advance by stages of progress; to carry
on with success through an ordeal, examination, or action; specifically,
to give legal or official sanction to; to ratify; to enact; to approve
as valid and just; <as>as, he <ex>passed</ex> the bill through the
committee; the senate <ex>passed</ex> the law</as>.</def> <sd>(e)</sd>
<def>To put in circulation; to give currency to; <as>as, to
<ex>pass</ex> counterfeit money</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Pass</xex> the
happy news.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Tennyson.</au> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>To cause to
obtain entrance, admission, or conveyance; <as>as, to <ex>pass</ex> a
person into a theater, or over a railroad</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To emit from the bowels; to evacuate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To take a turn with (a line,
gasket, etc.), as around a sail in furling, and make secure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Fencing)</fld> <def>To make, as a thrust, punto,
etc.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Passed midshipman</b></col>. <cd>See under
Midshipman.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass a dividend</b></col>, <cd>to omit
the declaration and payment of a dividend at the time when due.</cd> --
<col><b>To pass away</b></col>, <cd>to spend; to waste.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Lest
she <xex>pass away</xex> the flower of her age.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ecclus. xlii.
9.</au><-- (b) to die --> -- <col><b>To pass by</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To disregard; to neglect</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To excuse; to spare;
to overlook.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass off</b></col>, <cd>to impose
fraudulently; to palm off.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Passed</xex> himself
<xex>off</xex> as a bishop.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Macaulay.</au> --
<mcol><col><b>To pass (something) on (some one)</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>To pass (something) upon (some one)</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to put
upon as a trick or cheat; to palm off.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧She <xex>passed</xex>
the child <xex>on</xex> her husband for a boy.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au>
-- <col><b>To pass over</b></col>, <cd>to overlook; not to note or
resent; <as>as, to <ex>pass over</ex> an affront</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pass</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pass
<hw>Pass</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>pas</ets> (for sense 1),
and <ets>passe</ets>, fr. <ets>passer</ets> to pass. See <er>Pass</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An opening, road, or track,
available for passing; especially, one through or over some dangerous or
otherwise impracticable barrier; a passageway; a defile; a ford; <as>as,
a mountain <ex>pass</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧Try not the <qex>pass</qex>!⟦rdquo⟧ the old man said.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fencing)</fld> <def>A thrust or push; an attempt to
stab or strike an adversary.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A movement of the hand over or along anything; the
manipulation of a mesmerist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Rolling Metals)</fld> <def>A single passage of a
bar, rail, sheet, etc., between the rolls.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>State of things; condition; predicament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have his daughters brought him to this <qex>pass</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matters have been brought to this <qex>pass</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Permission or license to pass, or to go and come; a
psssport; a ticket permitting free transit or admission; <as>as, a
railroad or theater <ex>pass</ex>; a military
<ex>pass</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A ship sailing under the flag and <qex>pass</qex> of an enemy.</q>
<rj><qau>Kent.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Fig.: a thrust; a sally of wit.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Estimation; character.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Common speech gives him a worthy <qex>pass</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Passus</er>.]</ety> <def>A part; a
division.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Sports)</fld> <def>In football, hockey, and other
team sports, a transfer of the ball, puck, etc., to another player of
one's own team, usually at some distance. In American football, the
<ex>pass</ex> is through the air by an act of throwing the
ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pass boat</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a punt, or
similar boat.</cd> -- <col><b>Pass book</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A
book in which a trader enters articles bought on credit, and then passes
or sends it to the purchaser</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>See <er>Bank
book</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Pass box</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a
wooden or metallic box, used to carry cartridges from the service
magazine to the piece.</cd> -- <col><b>Pass check</b></col>, <cd>a
ticket of admission to a place of entertainment, or of readmission for
one who goes away in expectation of returning.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Passable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pass
<hw>Pas`s⟦eacute⟧"</hw>, <pos>masc.</pos>
\'d8
